#X text 35 26 A formant is a prominent spectral peak produced by a resonance in a sound-producing system. Hence \, they reinforce spectral peaks at given frequencies with a specific amplitude. Most notably \, the shape of the mouth and vocal tract can produce multiple formants depending on the vowel \, but musical instruments also have formants \, like the body of a violin \, the tube of a clarinet or the soundboard of a piano \, which all introduce resonances that shape their characteristic timbre., f 53;
#X text 35 173 Formant synthesis generates sounds by shaping the spectrum with resonant peaks and is commonly used to produce vowel-like sounds. Since formant synthesis models the resonances of physical sound producing systems \, it can be regarded as a simplified form of acoustic or physical modeling., f 53;
#X text 34 267 There are different Formant Synthesis techniques. A common one is to feed an excitation signal \, such as a pulse train or noise \, through resonant filters tuned to the desired formant frequencies. Let's start with this idea., f 53;
